Rating: 4
I have been wanting to make this cake for some time now and I finally did it over the weekend. I'm a huge chocolate cake fan, but strangley enough, I don't like cake and icing. I like my chocolate cake to be moist, dense, rich and not bready, crumby, dry with the sugary sweet icing piled on top like you see at most bday parties. I was drawn to this recipe bec of the ingredients. My cake turned out fantastic. It is not as dense as I would have wished for but I'm not complaining bec it really is a great choc cake. Next time i will do thinner layers of cake and spread the ganache in between to add moisture to the finished product. I topped it with fresh raspberries and drizzled raspberry coulis on the side. YUM! be aware: this is a very rich choc cake. You must love chocolate to enjoy this. I used Callebaut chocolate and non-dutch cocoa. You can get these items at whole foods. I'm a fan of quality ingredients and I can def taste the difference. The prior reviewer complained that this cake called for veg oil and not butter but oil adds more moisture to a cake. Creaming (butter) creates air bubbles, which lead to a lighter texture. Oil coats the protein molecules in the flour more quickly, preventing the formation of gluten, making the final product denser, but moist and tender. Since i prefer a denser cake, I prefer the oil. My suggestion: buy Callebaut chocolate and follow recipe as is. As said above, I will use thinner layers next time so that there is more ganache throughout each slice.

