Rating: 4
This is my second time making this cake. As most of the other 1336 reviewers have said, it is great! I followed the recipe to the letter including the 10" pans. I do have three tips to offer: the first is, the cake is truly better after a couple of days. I made this on a Thursday and the pieces we ate on Sunday night were the best yet. It has not dried out or gotten stale in the least. I did cover and refrigerate as the recipe directs, although admit I'm not sure why the cake requires refrigeration. Perhaps that's why it is keeping so well. The second tip is, it is way, WAY better at room temperature, so if you follow the instructions to refrigerate it, cut the pieces you're going to eat several hours in advance and let them sit out to come to room temp first. The reason is that the ganache gets too hard in the fridge. It's kind of like a semi-hard candy bar on top of the cake if it's still too cool - which isn't a great combination of textures. At absolute room temperature, though, the texture is perfect. The third tip has to do with the frosting. I saw some comments about the ganache being too runny to frost the cake. That is because you didn't let it sit long enough as the recipe says. After mixing, let it cool to room temp (starts out warm), stirring occasionally. For me it took 30-45 minutes. The texture became absolutely lovely - perfect for spreading and looking gorgeous. So, just be patient and allow time for the frosting to set up just enough, and you won't be disappointed.

Rating: 4
Very happy family! I don't own oil, so I used clarified butter (ghee), reduced the sugar by 3/4 cup, and the flour and cocoa by 1/4 cup each. Based on the reviews, I used 4 medium eggs and 4 oz bittersweet chocolate for the cake, and mixed the batter in a more old-fashioned way. Baked for 35 mins in 3x9" pans; all three rose perfectly to equal height. Took the hint of making ganache while the cake baked. It wasn't runny; I chopped the chocolate very finely in the food processor and simply poured the hot cream down the funnel with the machine still running. I whipped what was left of the pint of heavy cream, added it to just less than half the chocolate mixture, and used this between the layers; sufficient ganache left for the outside. Perfect texture, moist, not too sweet, no oily taste. Yum...

