Rating: 4
I followed the recipe using three 9" cake cans and filling the pans 1/2 way. I used a spray containing flour and oil on the pans, lined the pans with parchment and sprayed again - no problem with sticking. The cakes came out perfectly. Had a tiny bit of batter left. I put the frosting in the freezer and stirred every few minutes - it was ready to spread in about 10 minutes. I lined the top of the frosted cake with fresh raspberries and served with barely sweetened whipped cream. It was a major hit. Beautiful cake that looks like it came from a bakery...super moist and cuts beautifully. Very rich - this cake should serve 20 easily.

Rating: 4
This cake WAS delicious and over the top rich BUT be careful with your pan size as other reviewers have mentioned. I used two 9" cake pans, which I believe is what most of us have in our cabinets. Although I left some batter in the bowl, I still ended up overfilling the pans, and the batter ran over and burned on the bottom of the oven. It was a terrible mess and I wondered if it would ruin the flavor of the cakes because of the smoke issue inside the oven and the fact that I opened and closed the oven door multiple times during baking, trying to remove the biggest globs of batter. The cakes came out of the oven BLACK because of the dark chocolate and I thought they were ruined, so dark was the color. However, they were absolutely delicious! If you have 9" pans, three would be perfect to use with this recipe. I also second the need for greasing and flouring and then using parchment paper on the bottom of the cake pans(also greased and floured). It's a good rule of thumb to follow in most cases anyway to be on the safe side. There's nothing worse than to loose a layer of cake on the bottom of a pan which always makes frosting it so much more difficult!

