Rating: 4
The texture of this cake is firm and it has a medium crumb. Very moist. Almost gooey. Very delicious. There is a huge difference with the frosting between using gourmet chocolate and the store bought w/o the cocoa butter. And the ganache handles differently depending on that as well. It is very creamy and over the top delicious with the proper chocolate. You need to let it set to firm up before using, so allow extra time for this. My customers rave about this and come back again and again to order whole ones for gifts. Be safe and bake with trays under your pans. Until you get a feel for it, it can have a tendency to run over while baking. Always use parchment to line sheets. You will be a happier baker if you do. This is moist and chocolately just the way a chocolate cake should be. Not at all airy or fluffy. I have nothing negative to say about this recipe. And neither do my customers. I follow the recipe as written, no changes at all. (except I do vary the fillings, decor, etc....) Try this, you will not be disappointed.

Rating: 4
One other thing - 300 degrees is fine if it's convection bake - but too slow if it's not. Try 325 for conventional ovens.

Rating: 4
I've made this cake several times; exactly as written and, subsequently, with a little tinkering. I found it at its best when I reduced the sugar by 1/2 cup and used a half cup of melted butter & quarter cup of walnut oil for the vegetable oil. The results were an even better flavor and texture - really superb. (I find, often, that cakes that rely on oil alone can result in a cake with a heavy, greasy and unappealing crumb.)

