Rating: 4
OM freaking G!! This has to be the most beautiful cake I've made. I am not a pro baker and made more of a proletariat version of the cake using Ghiradelli chocolate and hershey's cocoa in the cake and Nestle's mini chocolate chips in the frosting. You don't HAVE to use the finer chocolate, but I'm sure it does lend a more refined flavor perhaps. I made several mistakes making the cake and it still turned out moist and wonderful. I did not let the eggs warm to room temp. I used two 9 inch pans since I couldn't find 10 inch pans. I totally forgot to preheat the oven until the batter was poured in the pans. Oh well. All turned out well. The frosting is easy and divine. To those who said it was too runny, I think they probably didn't let it rest long enough or chill it. I left mine on the counter and, after a few hours,it was fudgey goodness. I did a crumb coat, chilled it in the fridge and then finished it up with room temp frosting. It's similar to a Martha Stewart recipe (Mrs Millman's frosting?) but came out so much better. It's quite good on strawberries as well I might add. All in all, a delicious cake that even a baking flunky like me can make (and look good too).

Rating: 4
Have made this a zillion times and it is a winner, no doubt. Few points, for those who do not have "hot brewed coffee" at hand, I put in a tablespoon of instant with equivalent amount of water mentioned in recipe. For those who want to substitute the buttermilk, natural yogurt works beautifully. As for the frosting, 2 points to be made: Definitely make it 1-1/2 the amount for a comfortable spread. 2nd point is the amount of fine dark chocolate ( I used excellent 70% stuff) it asks for is unnecessary and too costly. I buy 4 bars of 100g of dark chocolate every time, 75 g go into the cake as mentioned in recipe, the other 325g are used for the Ganash (remember done at 1 and 1/2 times the amount) and it comes out dark as night and luscious! If I were to follow the recipe (at 1 and 1/2 ratio) I would be at 750g of chocolate, even at the stated amount in recipe, which is 500g for ganash plus the 75g for the cake, total of almost 600g...Unnecessary and too expensive!

