Rating: 4
Don't bother chopping up the chocolate !! When I'm in a hurry and don't have fancy chocolate around, I use Baker squares and don't even break them in half. The hot coffee in the batter, and then the hot cream in the ganache, when left to sit covering the chocolate... well, it melts just fine as you stir it. Now, the gigantic Scharrfen Berger (sp?) blocks may be a different story, but coarsely chopped has always worked for me. DO be very very careful to look at the pans used in this recipe. I find that three foil pans (8 1/2 inches) work perfectly for a three layer cake, but you have to skimp on the ganache between layers. If you don't have the 10" pans and you glob it all into 9" pans, you will have a volcanic mess on your hands ! The three layer cake is a little precarious to transport and slice but it is lovely. The cake almost tastes like a brownie, but it has a nice satisfying cake texture and is well worth the learning curve. For the people who say it's too complicated: try try again. For the people who say it's a simple cake to make and they did it in ten minutes while simultaneously cooking dinner for their kids: don't sandbag us, man !! Once you've made it, it's simple, but it does involve sifting and melting and brewing coffee and happening to have buttermilk on hand !! But when you've made it once successfully, you'll make it again in ten minutes (who knows, maybe while multitasking even!! and you'll throw all your other chocolate cake recipes away.

