Rating: 1
I bake cakes all the time and was excited to try this one since it received such great reviews. I followed the directions precisely and did not skip one step. The cake is okay. It's definitely moist and has a nice texture, but it's lacking in the flavor department. It doesn't have the subtle nuances of butter and brown sugar -- two ingredients I've found in my favorite chocolate cakes. There are some cake recipes (such as the caramel-milk chocolate cake here on Epicurious) that have better flavor and aren't quite as sweet. This one was almost too sweet for me. I didn't bother to make the frosting for this one. I'm sure it's good, but I will probably end up throwing this one out or using it as a practice cake for decorating. I'm really disappointed the cake didn't turn out and pretty shocked at all the great reviews.

Rating: 4
I have reviewed this cake before--I LOVE it, but I wanted to add another review because this time I did two things differently that might be useful for others: because of time constraints, I had to make the cake layers three days ahead, so I wrapped them tightly and froze them. Not only did they taste fine, but because they were cold when I frosted them, the frosting thickened as I put it on--which was great because there have been times that the frosting has been quite drippy. (It always turns out okay, but there are some nervous moments!) I think I'll plan on freezing them from now on. Second, because it was a special day, I spent a small fortune on Sharfenberger (sp?) chocolate. Not necessary. Many of my family have had this cake before and they (and I) both thought there was not a difference between the solid gold version and the ones I've made previously with Ghiradelli. btw, I always put raspberries between the layers and I've found that frozen work better than fresh. yumyum! enjoy!!

