Rating: 4
The cake is wonderful, and really is fail-safe. As there is a large amount of dry ingredients to put together, I found after mixing wet and dry together that I had ommitted 2 cups of the sugar (by taste) so I stirred more sugar in. This did NOT make the cake tough! Silicon cake pans did not need liners nor greasing. I patted finely chopped hazelnuts around the exterior ganache for presentation and taste. For better than 20 years I have normally made a frosting by mixing equal measures of sour cream and melted chocolate chips, and likely will do that next time as it's even easier than this ganache. I did not have trouble cutting the ganache-frosted cake straight from the refrigerator, but used a serrated blade so that might help. I had taken the time to distill ALL the reviews' information about pan sizes, chocolate options and filling options down to 3 pages so I'd have plenty of options for the future. I normally make the Easiest, Best Chocolate Mousse Cake from "Instant Gratification" by Lauren Chattman or Alice Medrich's Reine de Saba as both cakes are none fail and easy, and easily altered according to my whim of the moment. This chocolate layer cake fits with my desires for ease and adaptability--and that's saying a LOT. Thank you for this recipe, and thanks to all the reviewers whose information is so helpful.

