I made this cake for New Year's 2004. I love the cake, but the frosting could have been better. I found that if you refrigerate the frosting, the texture isn't that great (and I used the expensive Callabaut chocolate for the frosting!) I think it is much better if you leave it at room temp. The cake however, is exactly what I've been looking for! I used 3 oz of a Ghiradelli semi-sweet baking bar. I ended up using a chocolate buttercream for the middle of the cake because the ganache frosting really wasn't enough for the whole cake. Make this cake, you'll love it!

Rating: 4
This is the only chocolate cake I make, and I make it about 20 times a year! I make all the birthday cakes in our family and it is always this one. I make it in 3 8" round pans for the adults and 2 large sheet pans for the kids. I skip the ganache part and use swiss meringue buttercream (martha stewart kids magazine) or chocolate whip cream icing (epicurious) as I like to decorate the cakes. this is such an easy recipe, you cannot mess it up. I actually forgot the 3 cups of sugar once and only noticed (when my 2 year old exclaimed "yuk" when she began to lick the beaters)after i had poured the batter into the three pans and put them in the oven. I quickly poured it all back into the mixing bowl, added the sugar and baked. it was perfect! This cake also freezes well. I slice the leftover cake into one serving slices and freeze individually in rubbermaid containers. It thaws in about 15 minutes and YUM, what a treat out of the freezer. ONE IMPORTANT TIP... I line my pans with parchment and then oil with vegetable oil. Instead of using flour to coat the pan, use COCOA, it won't turn the cake edges white.

Rating: 4
I love this cake every time I make it--easy and delicious! It also works well for cupcakes. Just bake at the given temperature for 20-25 minutes. The recipe makes about 36 cupcakes and one batch of ganache is sufficient for all of them.

