Rating: 4
As a cooking teacher and after reading all those reviews, I had to make this cake! Made the cakes (two 9" rounds plus one 6" round, each filled about half way--they all rose beautifully just to the top of the pan) on Thursday evening, filled/frosted on Friday evening, served to guests Saturday afternoon, then had the 6" cake on Sunday afternoon with a fellow cooking teacher. All were moist and delicious! This is a very intensely chocolate cake, almost black in color. I used Valrhona cocoa powder and Ghiraradelli semisweet in the cake and half Callebaut and half Hershey's Special Dark for the frosting. I made no changes to the recipe and it came out perfectly, although I did watch the baking time (can't say exactly how long it took, as I just kept checking it every few minutes after about 40 minutes, but I know it was less than the stated time). I let the cakes cool about 10 minutes in the pans, then removed to a rack to cool completely. If you ever leave the cake in the pan too long and can't get it out, just return it to a warm oven for a few minutes (to soften the fat which has hardened). By the way, I can't stand the taste of coffee but couldn't detect it in the finished cake; however, I know from experience that using it cuts down on the sweetness. A wonderful cake, but a certain style that you have to like (my husband, for instance, much prefers the dense, flourless "decadent" style of chocolate cake). My feeling is that there's room in the culinary world for all of them!

