This recipe received rave reviews and was called "better than the best chocolate cake I've ever had in a fine restaurant". I used a darker cocoa (not dutch-processed) and the cake was really black so I whipped the ganache to lighten the color for more contrast and to make it more spreadable. I also baked it in 2-9 in. pans (3 in. deep) because my oven is too small for 2-10 in. pans. I torted the layers to make 4 instead of 2 because they were thicker. I've been begged to bake it again...soon!

Rating: 4
This cake is terrific - I've made it three times. The first time, I made the layers as written and used a cream cheese icing - it was delicious, but perhaps a little sweet. I love sweet desserts, and almost never reduce the sugar in a recipe, but the last two times I made this (including last week for my son's birthday) I cut a FULL CUP of sugar from the recipe, and used a regular buttercream icing. It was still terrific, though I felt not quite as moist as with the full complement of sugar. I think next time I would make this with two cups plus three tablespoons of sugar. Also, I have never made the ganache - if it's not too sweet, perhaps three cups of sugar in the batter makes sense. Anyway, a really yummy cake. I too have been looking for a good chocolate cake recipe - they are usually either too dry or too fudgy or not chocolaty enough. This one rises high, is really chocolaty, but is still a cake, not a candy or brownie like some you find. I think the buttermilk makes a huge difference in the height of the cake. By the way, the birthday rendition was in a 9 by 13 pan - worked just fine. This recipe is a major keeper - my search is over. - Regards.

