Rating: 4
Whenever I need a classic, rich chocolate layer cake, this will be the recipe I go to. My changes: I used dry buttermilk powder and bittersweet chocolate because that's what I could find. The result was a super-moist, dense, rich, chocolately cake. You don't taste the coffee at all and I used a very strong blend. I made the cake and frosting the day before I needed them and did not refrigerate either overnight. I had no problems with dryness or the frosting being too hard - it was the perfect spreading consistency. If you have always been disappointed by the lack of chocolate flavour and dryness of chocolate cakes in the past, this is the recipe that will cure those chocolate cake woes forever.

Rating: 0
Dear Mexico - put 1.5 TBSP plain white vinegar in a measuring cup then fill it to 1.5 cups with plain milk - let it stand 10-15 minutes, then stir - this will sour the milk which can be used in place of buttermilk - good luck

