Rating: 4
Excellent chocolate cake recipe. Having made it many times, here's what I have learnt. First, don't use cake flour - this is a recipe for a dense, moist cake and not a fluffy one. Second, you can use dutch process cocoa. Examples include cocoa barry (preferred) and most other imported cocoa. I disagree with a previous reviewer who calculated the required increase in leavening agents. Don't increase them. Just use dutch process cocoa and leave all other quanitities the same. The weakest part of the recipe is the ganache. If you absolutely must use a ganache, then do it the Cordon Bleu way. 1/2 heavy cream and one tablespoon light corn syrup heated and then added slowly, with stirring, to a bowl containing approximately 1 cup chopped chocolate (e.g. Callebaut or Belcolade) of the highest quality you can find. See http://www.cooking.com/recipes/static/recipe1822.htm Personally, I prefer the mousse frosting recipe that got rave reviews on this site. See http://www.epicurious.com/run/recipe/view?id=102230 and the sugar syrup is often a good idea. Finally, we taste with our eyes (French saying) so decorate your cake in the following manner: http://www.epicurious.com/run/recipe/view?id=105184 and click on the picture icon. One last thing (and I know I'll get yelled at for this) this recipe halves fine and you can actually mix all the wet ingredients in a blender and, space permiting, add the dry mix in their too and stir very much without problems. The "just combined well" part of this recipe applies to many cakes, but not this one.

