Rating: 4
A deep, dark, enormous, delicious cake! Amazing, too, because I had to convert to metric measurements, and make substitutions: used cake flour, and most imortant, because all our cocoa powders are Dutch process, I could not use baking soda so had to work out the baking powder equivalent (5 teasp) and used 1/2 t baking soda. AND I made a mistake and used only 2 cups of sugar! I can't understand the few problems people reported. If you butter the pans and shake in a little flour, it comes out so easily and does not break up. The ganache I made out of local dark Cadbury Bournville choc (300g) and 200g Swiss milk choc. (This comes to just over a pound) It chilled to a beautiful glossy spreading consistency. The batter was of a perfect consistency. The lack of a full cup of (castor/superfine) sugar doesn't seem to matter. I baked it for just over an hour. Size of pans not a problem. Glorious, moist, tender and full-flavoured -- death by chocolate! Just follow the recipe and do not (as someone did) use honey in place of the syrup for the ganache. I used golden syrup (cane syrup). Honey has water in it, which could make your ganache seize up into a gritty mess. Three Michelin stars for this recipe!!!

