Rating: 3
A very dense, brownie-like cake. My batter was so thick, I was afraid I was going to make a cookie. The flavor was amazing, but I think I overbaked it a little--I definitely shouldn't have done the full hour, though when I checked the cake at 50 minutes as recommended by reviews, it was still damp. Unfortunately, by the time I took it out, the cake turned dry and crumbly. Next time I'll decrease the baking time and up the moisture, maybe use a steam bath, and lighten the batter by beating the yolks and whites separately. The ganache looked a bit much, so I basically whipped heavy cream with a cup of powdered sugar, spread the topping on the cake and drizzled a mixture of blackberry preserves and pulverized marionberries on top. The lightness of the cream and the slight tartness of the fruit offset the flavor and texture perfectly. The texture was good, but not quite what I was looking for at the time--a very fine crumb, not unlike pound cake. My favorite chocolate cake of all time is still the Chocolate Crunch Layer Cake right here from epicurious.com. I guess I was looking for a cake to overturn that Platonic Ideal (moist, fluffy, dark, not too sweet), but this wasn't it. Still, definitely worth my while making, and I foresee this being a standard birthday cake for chocoholic friends.

