Rating: 0
Just fyi, if you can get your hands on buttermilk once in awhile, you can always freeze it and then use it in baking with good results. Or, lots of stores nowadays have a buttermilk powder that you add water to to mix up in the quantity you need; personally I dislike the aftertaste with this mix, and gave my whole container away after trying it once, but lots of people do use it. Or, you could always go the home-soured milk route--milk with a little cider vinegar (or lemon juice, but I like the vinegar more). That latter is what I generally do.

